{"id": "9810cc7b-8487-40e0-9cca-a97c9958dac6", "value": "\"Tenement houses, also known as Chinese shop-houses in Hong Kong, are characterised by a narrow street frontage of four to five metres (13-16ft), dictated by the length of Chinese fir poles, which were used as floor joists, and long narrow rooms between nine and 18 metres (30-60ft) covering an average floor area of 42-60 square metres (450-650 sq ft). They vary between two and four storeys, are lined up in a continuous fa\u00e7ade and connected to each other by 46cm (18 inch) thick party walls, later constructed of reinforced concrete. The facades of tenement houses often display wrought iron narrow balconies or verandas, which cover the entire pavement at ground level to protect pedestrians from sun exposure or torrential rains. Tenement house interiors comprise a commercial unit on the ground floor and residences on the upper floors. Non-structural partitions separate rooms inside each flat and \u2018cookhouses\u2019 are found in the rear of the building with openings to a back lane or next to air-wells for ventilation. This building typology is commonly found in southern China, preserving the idea of a live-work environment. It also traveled with the different waves of Chinese immigration to South and Southeast Asian parts of the globe and is still evident - albeit differently named and varying according to local indigenous or colonial influences - in Macau, Malacca, Penang, Singapore, Vietnam and Thailand.\"\n\n[Source: http://acp.arch.hku.hk/impact/glossary.html]"}

skos:Concept.skos:scopeNote: {"id": "8328958c-dcfb-41f7-a9ba-658ede8f7ca9", "value": "In many ancestral halls in northern China, mirror walls have long been a common feature. As dynasties in the north were overthrown, their officials emigrated south, bringing with them their cultural knowledge. As a result, some halls in southern villages convey northern architectural influences. The purpose of these walls is two-fold. First, cold winds and dust are kept from entering the hall. Second, bad spirits are prevented from entering the structure. The latter is rooted in Feng Shui \u98a8\u6c34 \n\n[Source: http://acp.arch.hku.hk/impact/glossary.html]"}
